A four-year-old boy has died after he ‘wandered off’ and fell into a canal in Walsall yesterday. Emergency services rushed to the scene, in the town of Bloxwich after the alarm was raised. Police officers managed to pull the child from the water, but despite the best efforts of paramedics he could not be revived. He was pronounced dead shortly after arriving at hospital by air ambulance. West Midlands Police said they were alerted to a report of a child in the water at around 12.15pm on Friday. A spokesperson from the force said: ‘There are no suspicious circumstances and our thoughts are with his family, and the rest of the community, at this deeply distressing time.’ The canal, nearby homes and a small playpark were blocked off by a cordon following the tragedy. A West Midlands Ambulance Service spokesperson added that they had been called at 12.16pm to the incident, off Razorbill Way. The spokesperson added: ‘Two ambulances, two paramedic officers a critical care car from Midlands Air Ambulance and the Midlands Air Ambulance from Cosford attended the scene. ‘Upon arrival we found a child in a critical condition. He received treatment from ambulance staff on scene. ‘He was conveyed to Birmingham Children’s Hospital for further treatment.’ The boy is thought to have wandered off from his home before he was spotted in the canal by a passer-by, the Sun reports. His identity has not been released by police. Get in touch with our news team by emailing us at webnews@metro.co.uk. For more stories like this, check our news page. 